The paper discusses the privacy implications of airdrops, which involves analyzing blockchain data and identifying patterns in address ownership. This falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR) and cybercrime (cs.CY). The paper also uses address clustering techniques, which are commonly used in database systems (cs.DB). Additionally, the paper discusses the sharing of addresses between different blockchains, which relates to the topic of system integration (cs.SI). Finally, the paper involves analyzing large amounts of data, which falls under the category of distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC).
